Q: Can you figure out why the following doesn't work?

\documentclass[letterpaper]{article}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usepackage[margin=0pt]{geometry}% overlapping the margins is easier than changing them.

\usepackage{adjustbox}
\newsavebox{\bigbox}
\parindent=0pt

\begin{document}
\savebox\bigbox{\scalebox{1.33}{\begin{tikzpicture}
\fill[green] (0,0) rectangle (\textwidth,\textheight);
\foreach \u in {10,20,...,360} {
\pgfmathsetmacro{\stepu}{cos(\u)+2}
\pgfmathsetmacro{\stepv}{sin(\u)+2}
\draw[red,thick] ({\stepu in},{\stepv in}) rectangle ++(4.5in,7in);}
\node[scale=2] at (current page.center) {Sewing pattern};
\end{tikzpicture}}}

\clipbox{0pt 0.33\textheight 0.33\textwidth 0pt}{\usebox\bigbox}% upper left

\clipbox{0pt 0pt 0.33\textwidth \textheight}{\usebox\bigbox}% lower left

\clipbox{\textwidth 0.33\textheight 0pt 0pt}{\usebox\bigbox}% upper right

\clipbox{\textwidth 0pt 0pt \textheight}{\usebox\bigbox}% lower right

\end{document}

A: The trim arguments involving lengths need to be inside braces. The arguments are separated by spaces and the length names eat the spaces.

\documentclass[letterpaper]{article}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usepackage[margin=0pt]{geometry}% overlapping the margins is easier than changing them.

\usepackage{adjustbox}
\newsavebox{\bigbox}
\parindent=0pt

\begin{document}
\savebox\bigbox{\scalebox{1.33}{\begin{tikzpicture}
\fill[green] (0,0) rectangle (\textwidth,\textheight);
\foreach \u in {10,20,...,360} {
\pgfmathsetmacro{\stepu}{cos(\u)+2}
\pgfmathsetmacro{\stepv}{sin(\u)+2}
\draw[red,thick] ({\stepu in},{\stepv in}) rectangle ++(4.5in,7in);}
\node[scale=2] at (current page.center) {Sewing pattern};
\end{tikzpicture}}}

\clipbox{0pt {0.33\textheight} {0.33\textwidth} 0pt}{\usebox\bigbox}% upper left

\clipbox{0pt 0pt {0.33\textwidth} {\textheight}}{\usebox\bigbox}% lower left

\clipbox{{\textwidth} {0.33\textheight} 0pt 0pt}{\usebox\bigbox}% upper right

\clipbox{{\textwidth} 0pt 0pt {\textheight}}{\usebox\bigbox}% lower right

\end{document}

Q: I'm trying with:

\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{endnotes}
\usepackage{hyperref}

\begin{document}

This is for test\endnote{“General Election: Trump vs. Biden,” RealClear
Politics, accessed June 24, 2021,
\url{https://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2020/president/us/general_election_trump_vs_biden-6247.html#polls}.}

\theendnotes

\end{document}

It produced the error:

! Illegal parameter number in definition of \next.
<to be read again>
p
l.9 ..._election_trump_vs_biden-6247.html#polls}.}

If I remove the character
#
then it works fine, same kind of error comes when using
%
character in
URL

Please advise how can I achieve this.

A: You get essentially the same error if you don't use
endnotes
and replace
\endnote
with
\footnote
:

! Illegal parameter number in definition of \Hy@tempa.
<to be read again>
p
l.13 ...election_trump_vs_biden-6247.html#polls}.}

You can use
xurl
and
enotez
:

\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{enotez}
\usepackage{xurl}
\usepackage{hyperref}

\begin{document}

This is for test\endnote{“General Election: Trump vs. Biden,” RealClear
Politics, accessed June 24, 2021,
\url{https://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2020/president/us/general_election_trump_vs_biden-6247.html#polls}.}

\printendnotes

\end{document}

If you insist with
endnotes

\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{endnotes}
\usepackage{xurl}
\usepackage{hyperref}

\urldef{\trumpbiden}\url{https://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2020/president/us/general_election_trump_vs_biden-6247.html#polls}

\begin{document}

This is for test\endnote{“General Election: Trump vs. Biden,” RealClear
Politics, accessed June 24, 2021, \trumpbiden.}

\theendnotes

\end{document}

Q: Is it the
bracealign
package that generates such large exponents equal to the base of the power?

\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{bracealign}
\begin{document}
\[
\begin{bracealign}
= x^{\overbrace{(m+1)+\cdots+(m+1)}^{k}}
= x_{\underbrace{(m+1)+\cdots+(m+1)}_{k}}
\end{bracealign}
\]
\end{document}

A: bracealign
has nothing to do with this. The problem is that
\underbrace
and
\overbrace
force
\displaystyle
.

\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\makeatletter
\NewDocumentCommand{\obrace}{mm}{{\mathpalette\obrace@{{#1}{#2}}}}
\newcommand{\obrace@}[2]{\obrace@@#1#2}
\newcommand{\obrace@@}[3]{%
\mathop{\vbox{%
\m@th
\ialign{%
##\crcr
\noalign{\brace@kern{#1}}
\brace@size{#1}\selectfont\downbracefill\crcr
\noalign{\brace@kern{#1}\nointerlineskip}
$\hfil#1{#2}\hfil$\crcr
}%
}}\limits^{#3}%
}
\NewDocumentCommand{\ubrace}{mm}{{\mathpalette\ubrace@{{#1}{#2}}}}
\newcommand{\ubrace@}[2]{\ubrace@@#1#2}
\newcommand{\ubrace@@}[3]{%
\mathop{\vbox{%
\m@th
\ialign{%
##\crcr
$\hfil#1{#2}\hfil$\crcr
\noalign{\brace@kern{#1}\nointerlineskip}
\brace@size{#1}\selectfont\upbracefill\crcr
\noalign{\brace@kern{#1}}
}%
}}\limits_{#3}%
}
\newcommand{\brace@size}[1]{%
\fontsize{\ifx#1\displaystyle\f@size\else\ifx#1\textstyle\f@size\else\sf@size\fi\fi}{0}%
}
\newcommand{\brace@kern}[1]{%
\kern\ifx#1\displaystyle3\else\ifx#1\textstyle3\else2\fi\fi\p@
}
\makeatother

\begin{document}

\[
x^{\obrace{(m+1)+\cdots+(m+1)}{k}}
=
x_{\ubrace{(m+1)+\cdots+(m+1)}{k}}
\]

\end{document}

Q: I was trying to understand how the
easing
package works and whether it can be useful for plotting a sequence of functions in order to study uniform convergence. I am not sure whether the package only allows plotting a set of predefined functions, or whether it also enables the representation of arbitrary sequences of functions.

In particular, I would like to know whether there is a way to use this package (or other similar LaTeX packages) to effectively visualize any sequence of functions. If there is a more suitable tool, I would appreciate it if you could suggest it.

Additionally I not understand the reason of a ugly graph for
$n=1, 2$
. Here an example:

\documentclass{article}

\usepackage{pgfplots}
\usepgflibrary{easing}

\pgfplotsset{compat=1.18}

\begin{document}

\begin{center}

\begin{tikzpicture}

\begin{axis}[
width=12cm,
height=7cm,
domain=0:1,
axis equal image,
samples=300,
xmin=0,
xmax=1,
ymin=0,
ymax=1.05,
axis lines=left,
xlabel={$x$},
ylabel={$x^n$},
legend pos=north west,
thick
]

\pgfkeys{/easing/pow/exponent=1}
\addplot[blue] {poweasein(0,1,x)};
\addlegendentry{$n=1$}

\pgfkeys{/easing/pow/exponent=2}
\addplot[red] {poweasein(0,1,x)};
\addlegendentry{$n=2$}

\pgfkeys{/easing/pow/exponent=4}
\addplot[green!60!black] {poweasein(0,1,x)};
\addlegendentry{$n=4$}

\pgfkeys{/easing/pow/exponent=8}
\addplot[orange] {poweasein(0,1,x)};
\addlegendentry{$n=8$}

\addplot[black, dotted] { (x==1 ? 1 : 0) };
\addlegendentry{$\lim f_n$}

\end{axis}

\end{tikzpicture}

\end{center}

\end{document}

A: This answer only addresses the causes of the artifacts.

As far as I understand, the implementation of
pow
in the
easing
package does not compute powers directly, but instead approximates them via
e^{n\ln x}
. This seems to be why small numerical artifacts appear for
n=1
and
n=2
: for
n=1
, the package effectively computes
exp(ln(x))
rather than simply
x
.
So if one uses
easing
, it is better to use the special functions for small integer powers:

\addplot {lineareasein(0,1,x)}; % x
\addplot {quadeasein(0,1,x)}; % x^2
\addplot {cubiceasein(0,1,x)}; % x^3
\addplot {quarteasein(0,1,x)}; % x^4
\addplot {quinteasein(0,1,x)}; % x^5

These variants are implemented explicitly, unlike the general
pow
function.

Also, I would avoid using
\addplot[black, dotted] { (x==1 ? 1 : 0) };

It is better to draw the horizontal part and the isolated point separately, as in the following code:

\documentclass{article}

\usepackage{pgfplots}
\usepgflibrary{easing}

\pgfplotsset{compat=1.18}

\begin{document}

\begin{center}

\begin{tikzpicture}

\begin{axis}[
width=12cm,
height=7cm,
domain=0:1,
axis equal image,
samples=300,
xmin=0,
xmax=1.05,
ymin=0,
ymax=1.05,
axis lines=left,
xlabel={$x$},
ylabel={$x^n$},
legend pos=north west,
thick,
axis line style={black!30},
tick style={black!30},
]

\pgfkeys{/easing/pow/exponent=1}
%\addplot[blue] {poweasein(0,1,x)};
\addplot[blue] {lineareasein(0,1,x)}; % x
\addlegendentry{$n=1$}

\pgfkeys{/easing/pow/exponent=2}
%\addplot[red] {poweasein(0,1,x)};
\addplot[red] {quadeasein(0,1,x)}; % x^2
\addlegendentry{$n=2$}

\pgfkeys{/easing/pow/exponent=4}
%\addplot[green!60!black] {poweasein(0,1,x)};
\addplot[green!60!black] {quarteasein(0,1,x)}; % x^4
\addlegendentry{$n=4$}

\pgfkeys{/easing/pow/exponent=8}
\addplot[orange] {poweasein(0,1,x)};
\addlegendentry{$n=8$}

%\addplot[black, dotted] { (x==1 ? 1 : 0) };
\addplot[magenta, dotted, no marks,very thick] coordinates {(0,0) (1,0)};
\addplot[magenta, only marks, mark=*, mark size=1pt,] coordinates {(1,1)};
\addplot[magenta, only marks, mark=o, mark size=1pt, mark options={fill=white}, thin] coordinates {(1,0)};
\addlegendentry{$\lim f_n$}

\end{axis}

\end{tikzpicture}

\end{center}

\end{document}

I slightly changed the colors of the axes and of the graph of the limit function to make the limit function easier to see.

Q: For some reasons, I need to create a multi-column layout without using the popular packages for multi-column text. What I do is, I grab the text, set it inside a box of restricted
\hsize
, split the box with
\vbox_set_split_to_ht:NNn
. Then the split boxes are unpacked inside coffins, they are attached with some x offset and typeset. Have a look at the following MWE:

\documentclass{article}
\usepackage[margin=3cm]{geometry}
\usepackage{kantlipsum}
\usepackage{microtype}

\begin{document}
\ExplSyntaxOn
\vbox_set:Nn \l_tmpa_box {
\hsize = 0.475 \linewidth \prg_do_nothing:
\kant [ 1 - 3 ]
}

\vbox_set_split_to_ht:NNn \l_tmpb_box \l_tmpa_box {
\textheight
-
\baselineskip % to get the effect of a \vtop
}

\vcoffin_set:Nnn \l_tmpa_coffin { 0.475 \linewidth } {
\vbox_unpack_drop:N \l_tmpb_box
}

\vcoffin_set:Nnn \l_tmpb_coffin { 0.475 \linewidth } {
\vbox_unpack_drop:N \l_tmpa_box
}

\coffin_join:NnnNnnnn \l_tmpa_coffin { r } { t }
\l_tmpb_coffin { l } { t }
{ 0.025 \linewidth } \c_zero_dim

\coffin_typeset:Nnnnn \l_tmpa_coffin
{ l } { t }
\c_zero_dim \c_zero_dim
\ExplSyntaxOff
\end{document}

This produces:

I read that
\splittopskip
could be causing this, but it is 10pt which nearly is of a line's height and as can be seen from the screenshot, our difference is smaller than that. I tried
\lineskip
and that did produce a tiny amount of space which I thought could be related to the spurious space, but I require 3 times the
\lineskip
to get both the columns at the right position.

\documentclass{article}
\usepackage[margin=3cm]{geometry}
\usepackage{kantlipsum}
\usepackage{microtype}

\begin{document}
\ExplSyntaxOn
\vbox_set:Nn \l_tmpa_box {
\hsize = 0.475 \linewidth \prg_do_nothing:
\kant [ 1 - 3 ]
}

\vbox_set_split_to_ht:NNn \l_tmpb_box \l_tmpa_box {
\textheight
-
\baselineskip % to get the effect of a \vtop
}

\vcoffin_set:Nnn \l_tmpa_coffin { 0.475 \linewidth } {
\vbox_unpack_drop:N \l_tmpb_box
}

\vcoffin_set:Nnn \l_tmpb_coffin { 0.475 \linewidth } {
\vbox_unpack_drop:N \l_tmpa_box
}

\coffin_join:NnnNnnnn \l_tmpa_coffin { r } { t }
\l_tmpb_coffin { l } { t }
{ 0.025 \linewidth } { 3 \lineskip }

\coffin_typeset:Nnnnn \l_tmpa_coffin
{ l } { t }
\c_zero_dim \c_zero_dim
\ExplSyntaxOff
\end{document}

I am almost sure that
\lineskip
is not the correct macro to be used there, but then which one exactly is it? What stores the culprit skip/glue? What would be a recommended (and preferably L3) way of doing it?

A: The culprit is
\splittopskip
.
More precisely, after
\vsplit
, TeX inserts glue at the beginning of the remaining box of the form

\splittopskip - \ht(first line)

In this case this is about
3pt
, so the second column ends up slightly lower than the first one.

\lineskip
is not responsible here; it just happens to give a similar value.

One way to fix this is as follows: before the actual splitting, do an empty split to
0pt
. This inserts the same
\splittopskip
at the beginning of the material from which the first column will be split as TeX will later insert at the beginning of the remaining material.

Thus, in
\coffin_join
, the vertical offset should be kept zero.

I have marked the two relevant lines in your first example.

\documentclass{article}
\usepackage[margin=3cm]{geometry}
\usepackage{kantlipsum}
\usepackage{microtype}

\begin{document}
\ExplSyntaxOn
\vbox_set:Nn \l_tmpa_box {
\hsize = 0.475 \linewidth \prg_do_nothing:
\tex_penalty:D -10000 \scan_stop: % <=============================
\kant [ 1 - 3 ]
}

\box_new:N \l_my_discard_box % <================================

\vbox_set_split_to_ht:NNn \l_my_discard_box \l_tmpa_box
{ \c_zero_dim }

\vbox_set_split_to_ht:NNn \l_tmpb_box \l_tmpa_box {
\textheight
-
\baselineskip % to get the effect of a \vtop
}

\vcoffin_set:Nnn \l_tmpa_coffin { 0.475 \linewidth } {
\vbox_unpack_drop:N \l_tmpb_box
}

\vcoffin_set:Nnn \l_tmpb_coffin { 0.475 \linewidth } {
\vbox_unpack_drop:N \l_tmpa_box
}

\coffin_join:NnnNnnnn \l_tmpa_coffin { r } { t }
\l_tmpb_coffin { l } { t }
{ 0.025 \linewidth } \c_zero_dim

\coffin_typeset:Nnnnn \l_tmpa_coffin
{ l } { t }
\c_zero_dim \c_zero_dim
\ExplSyntaxOff
\end{document}

Q: I am trying to define a custom electrical symbol for use with
circuitikz
.

The symbol is a sinusoidal voltage source consisting of:

a circle,

a sinusoidal waveform inside the circle,

+
/
−
polarity markings,

and a voltage label such as
v_1
(which should be customizable).

I would like to implement it as a TikZ
pic
so that it behaves similarly to built-in
circuitikz
components and allows easy connection of wires to its terminals.

The symbol I want to reproduce is shown below (from Engineering Circuit Analysis by Hayt):

I noticed that
circuitikz
already provides a sinusoidal voltage source. If possible, I would like to use that existing implementation as a reference (or perhaps extend it) so that the custom symbol matches the standard
circuitikz
style, dimensions, and line thickness used by the library.

A: Here is one possible variant.

\documentclass[border=5pt]{standalone}
\usepackage[american]{circuitikz}

\makeatletter
\newdimen\haytSV@L
\newdimen\haytSV@r

\tikzset{
pics/hayt sV/.style args={#1}{
code={%
\haytSV@L=\pgf@circ@Rlen

\haytSV@r=.5\pgf@circ@Rlen
\haytSV@r=\ctikzvalof{bipoles/vsourcesin/height}\haytSV@r
\haytSV@r=\ctikzvalof{sources/scale}\haytSV@r

% External contacts
\coordinate (-plus) at (0, .5\haytSV@L);
\coordinate (-minus) at (0,-.5\haytSV@L);

% Useful anchors
\coordinate (-center) at (0,0);
\coordinate (-north) at (0, \haytSV@r);
\coordinate (-south) at (0,-\haytSV@r);
\coordinate (-east) at ( \haytSV@r,0);
\coordinate (-west) at (-\haytSV@r,0);

% Same names, if one prefers circuit-like terminology
\coordinate (-up) at (-plus);
\coordinate (-down) at (-minus);

% Standard circuitikz sinusoidal source body
\node[vsourcesinshape, rotate=90] at (0,0) {};

% Leads
\draw[line width=0.8pt] (0, .5\haytSV@L) -- (0, \haytSV@r);
\draw[line width=0.8pt] (0,-.5\haytSV@L) -- (0,-\haytSV@r);

% Polarity signs and voltage label
\node[inner sep=0pt, font=\scriptsize] at (0, .55\haytSV@r) {$+$};
\node[inner sep=0pt, font=\scriptsize] at (0,-.55\haytSV@r) {$-$};
\node[anchor=east, inner sep=1pt] at (-1.3\haytSV@r,0) {#1};
}
},
pics/hayt sV/.default={$v_1$}
}
\makeatother

\begin{document}

\begin{circuitikz}
\pic (V1) at (0,0) {hayt sV={$v_1$}};
\end{circuitikz}

\end{document}

You can see the anchors by adding the following code inside the circuitikz environment, after the
\pic
command:

% Visible anchors and labels
\foreach \p/\anchor/\dx/\dy in {
plus/south/0/2mm,
minus/north/0/-2mm,
center/east/-4mm/4mm,
north/west/2mm/0,
south/west/2mm/0,
east/west/6mm/0,
west/east/-2mm/0
}{
\fill[red] (V1-\p) circle[radius=.7pt];
\node[
font=\scriptsize,
anchor=\anchor,
xshift=\dx,
yshift=\dy
] at (V1-\p) {\texttt{V1-\p}};
}

To change the font or color of the label, modify the following line in the definition of the
pic
:

\node[anchor=east, inner sep=1pt] at (-1.3\haytSV@r,0) {#1};

Edit.

After Rmano's excellent answer, I hesitated about posting this revised version. In this variant the bipole is defined from scratch and can be used in
to[...]
paths.

In this particular case, Rmano's solution is certainly preferable. Still, this variant may be useful as a technical exercise, since it shows how to define a genuine new CircuitikZ bipole with its own internal drawing. It may also be useful for future users who need to define a similar custom component.

The bipole
hayt sV
is a custom CircuitikZ bipole, not a built-in source symbol. It can be used in
to[...]
paths like ordinary CircuitikZ bipoles; however, the sinusoidal symbol and the internal polarity signs are drawn manually. Its size can be adjusted using the parameters
bipoles/haytvsourcesin/height
and
bipoles/haytvsourcesin/width
.

The example below shows five such bipoles: four on the sides of a square and one on a diagonal.

\documentclass[border=5pt]{standalone}
\usepackage[american]{circuitikz}

\makeatletter

\newdimen\haytSV@rad
\newdimen\haytSV@sign
\newdimen\haytSV@plusy
\newdimen\haytSV@minusy

\ctikzset{bipoles/haytvsourcesin/height/.initial=.60}
\ctikzset{bipoles/haytvsourcesin/width/.initial=.60}

\pgfcircdeclarebipolescaled{sources}
{}
{\ctikzvalof{bipoles/haytvsourcesin/height}}
{haytvsourcesin}
{\ctikzvalof{bipoles/haytvsourcesin/height}}
{\ctikzvalof{bipoles/haytvsourcesin/width}}
{
% Circle
\pgf@circ@setlinewidth{bipoles}{\pgfstartlinewidth}
\pgfpathellipse
{\pgfpointorigin}
{\pgfpoint{0}{\pgf@circ@res@up}}
{\pgfpoint{\pgf@circ@res@left}{0}}
\pgf@circ@draworfill

% Save radius before changing \pgf@circ@res@up
\haytSV@rad=\pgf@circ@res@up

% Sinusoidal symbol
\pgf@circ@res@up=.5\pgf@circ@res@up
\pgfscope
\pgf@circ@sources@symbol@setup
\pgfpathmoveto{\pgfpoint{-\pgf@circ@res@up}{0cm}}
\pgfpathsine{\pgfpoint{.5\pgf@circ@res@up}{.5\pgf@circ@res@up}}
\pgfpathcosine{\pgfpoint{.5\pgf@circ@res@up}{-.5\pgf@circ@res@up}}
\pgfpathsine{\pgfpoint{.5\pgf@circ@res@up}{-.5\pgf@circ@res@up}}
\pgfpathcosine{\pgfpoint{.5\pgf@circ@res@up}{.5\pgf@circ@res@up}}
\pgfusepath{draw}
\endpgfscope

% Manual polarity signs, drawn as lines
\haytSV@sign=.25\haytSV@rad
\haytSV@plusy=.6\haytSV@rad
\haytSV@minusy=-.6\haytSV@rad

\pgfscope
\pgf@circ@sources@symbol@setup

% plus sign, above the sinusoid
\pgfpathmoveto{\pgfpoint{0pt}{\dimexpr\haytSV@plusy-\haytSV@sign\relax}}
\pgfpathlineto{\pgfpoint{0pt}{\dimexpr\haytSV@plusy+\haytSV@sign\relax}}

\pgfpathmoveto{\pgfpoint{\dimexpr-\haytSV@sign\relax}{\haytSV@plusy}}
\pgfpathlineto{\pgfpoint{\haytSV@sign}{\haytSV@plusy}}

% minus sign, below the sinusoid
\pgfpathmoveto{\pgfpoint{\dimexpr-\haytSV@sign\relax}{\haytSV@minusy}}
\pgfpathlineto{\pgfpoint{\haytSV@sign}{\haytSV@minusy}}

\pgfusepath{draw}
\endpgfscope
}

\pgfcirc@activate@bipole@opt{v}
{haytvsourcesin}
{haytvsourcesin}
{hayt sV}
{%
\circuitikzbasekey/bipole/is voltage=true,%
\circuitikzbasekey/bipole/is voltageoutsideofsymbol=true%
}

\makeatother

\begin{document}

\begin{circuitikz}
\coordinate (A) at (0,0);
\coordinate (B) at (4,0);
\coordinate (C) at (4,4);
\coordinate (D) at (0,4);

\draw
(A) to[hayt sV, l_=$v_1$] (B)
to[hayt sV, l_=$v_2$] (C)
to[hayt sV, l_=$v_3$] (D)
to[hayt sV, l_=$v_4$] (A)
to[hayt sV, l=$v_5$] (C);

\foreach \p in {A,B,C,D}{
\fill[red] (\p) circle[radius=1pt];
}
\end{circuitikz}

\end{document}

Q: The
bounty
expires
in 7 days
. Answers to this question are eligible for a
+100
reputation bounty.

Explorer
wants to
reward an existing answer
.

What I want is the arrow path patterns as below, but not only work for straight line, but ployline, curve, as path style/decoration:

\documentclass[tikz,border=6pt]{standalone}
\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}
\foreach \i in {1,...,5}
\draw[-latex,shorten >=2pt, shorten <=2pt] (\i,0) -- ({\i+1},0);
\end{tikzpicture}

\begin{tikzpicture}
\draw[-latex,shorten >=2pt, shorten <=2pt] (0.5,0) -- (1,0);
