Q: Suppose I need to plot data from many files using
pgfplots
, and these files are not properly formatted (8 header lines not prefixed with
%
or
#
, and commas instead of periods as decimal separators). This can be managed using the following code:

\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{pgfplots}
\pgfplotsset{compat=1.18}
\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}
\begin{axis}
\addplot table [skip first n=8,/pgf/number format/read comma as period] {data1.dat};
\addplot table [skip first n=8,/pgf/number format/read comma as period] {data2.dat};
\end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}

But it is tedious to have to specify these
table
options each time
\addplot table
appears.

I haven't found any way in the
pgfplots
documentation to declare these parameters in a (semi-)global manner. Have I missed something?

A: The key
skip first n
belongs to the
/pgfplots/table
family, so it can be set via
\pgfplotstableset
. The key
read comma as period
is in
/pgf/number format
, but it can also be set there as an absolute key.
Try any of these options:

\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{pgfplots}
\pgfplotsset{compat=1.18}

\pgfplotstableset{
skip first n=8,
/pgf/number format/read comma as period,
}

\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}
\begin{axis}
\addplot table {data1.dat};
\addplot table {data2.dat};
\end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}

or

\begin{tikzpicture}
\pgfplotstableset{
skip first n=8,
/pgf/number format/read comma as period,
}

\begin{axis}
\addplot table {data1.dat};
\addplot table {data2.dat};
\end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}

You can also define a named style:

\pgfplotstableset{
bad data files/.style={
skip first n=8,
/pgf/number format/read comma as period,
},
}

Q: I want to add a background picture for the page(s) that get created for using the
\part
command. But when I do this, the picture instead goes to the next side and not to the part page. How can I get the picture to the correct page?

MWE:

\documentclass{report}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usepackage[newparttoc]{titlesec}
\usepackage{titletoc}
\usepackage{tocloft}
\titleformat{\part}[display]{\Huge\scshape\filright\centering}{}{20pt}{\thispagestyle{empty}}
\titlecontents{part}[0pt]{\addvspace{2pc}\centering\large\bfseries}{}{}{}
\begin{document}
\part{A}\tikz[remember picture, overlay] \node[opacity=0.3, inner sep=0pt] at (current page.center){\includegraphics[width=\paperwidth, height=\paperheight]{example-image-a}};
\part{B}\tikz[remember picture, overlay] \node[opacity=0.3, inner sep=0pt] at (current page.center){\includegraphics[width=\paperwidth, height=\paperheight]{example-image-b}};
\end{document}

A: If you would like to manually add the background images, you could use hooks:

\documentclass{report}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usepackage[newparttoc]{titlesec}
\usepackage{titletoc}
\usepackage{tocloft}
\titleformat{\part}[display]{\Huge\scshape\filright\centering}{}{20pt}{\thispagestyle{empty}}
\titlecontents{part}[0pt]{\addvspace{2pc}\centering\large\bfseries}{}{}{}
\begin{document}
\clearpage
\AddToHookNext{shipout/background}{\tikz[remember picture, overlay] \node[opacity=0.3, inner sep=0pt] at (current page.center){\includegraphics[width=\paperwidth, height=\paperheight]{example-image-a}};}
\part{A}
some text in part A
\clearpage
\AddToHookNext{shipout/background}{\tikz[remember picture, overlay] \node[opacity=0.3, inner sep=0pt] at (current page.center){\includegraphics[width=\paperwidth, height=\paperheight]{example-image-b}};}
\part{B}
some text in part A
\end{document}

Or if your background images are somehow numbered, you could include them automatically base on the part number, e.g.

\documentclass{report}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usepackage[newparttoc]{titlesec}
\usepackage{titletoc}
\usepackage{tocloft}
\titleformat{\part}[display]{\Huge\scshape\filright\centering}{}{20pt}{\thispagestyle{empty}\tikz[remember picture, overlay] \node[opacity=0.3, inner sep=0pt] at (current page.center){\includegraphics[width=\paperwidth, height=\paperheight]{example-image-\alph{part}}};}
\titlecontents{part}[0pt]{\addvspace{2pc}\centering\large\bfseries}{}{}{}
\begin{document}
\part{A}
some text in part A
\part{B}
some text in part A
\end{document}

Q: The following is an MWE. My question is how to change the font size of 'Contents' (by the way, 'List of Figures', 'List of Tables') in header and body separately? That is to say, for example,
how to change the size of the title 'Contents' on the contents page, while dispaly it in header according to the size command in
\fancyhead
(same question for 'List of Figures' and 'List of Tables')?

\documentclass{book}
\usepackage{lipsum}
\renewcommand{\contentsname}{\Large Contents} % **The points where problems occur**
\renewcommand{\listfigurename}{\Large Figure}
\renewcommand{\listtablename}{\Large Table}
\begin{document}
\frontmatter
\tableofcontents
\listoffigures
\listoftables
\mainmatter
\chapter{Cha1}
\section{sec1}
\lipsum[1-8]
\end{document}

Unfortunately, the
\renewcommand
command simultaneously change the size in the header, even when I use the package
fancyhdr
to design a new page style as follows, where the size command in
\fancyhead
doesn't work for 'Contents', 'List of Figures' or 'List of Tables' at the time.

\documentclass{book}

\usepackage{fancyhdr}
\pagestyle{fancy}
\fancypagestyle{frontmatterstyle}{
\fancyhf{}
\fancyhead[EC]{\footnotesize\leftmark} % **Size command doesn't work for contentsname/listfigurename/listtablename in header**
\fancyhead[OC]{\footnotesize Test}
}

\usepackage{lipsum}
\renewcommand{\contentsname}{\Large Contents} % **The points where problems occur**
\renewcommand{\listfigurename}{\Large Figure}
\renewcommand{\listtablename}{\Large Table}
\begin{document}
\frontmatter
\pagestyle{frontmatterstyle}
\tableofcontents
\listoffigures
\listoftables
\mainmatter
\chapter{Cha1}
\section{sec1}
\lipsum[1-8]
\end{document}

I tried the relevant packages like
sectsty
,
titlesec
or
tocloft
, but I still failed. I don't know how to change them separately. Could someone do me a favor? Thanks a lot!

A: As already told in a comment to your other question, you should not redefine
\…name
macros using font settings (unless you want this font settings to be used whenever the
\…name
macro is used). For example
\tableofcontents
uses:

\@mkboth{\MakeUppercase\contentsname}{\MakeUppercase\contentsname}

so
{\footnotesize\leftmark}
in the page header definition of your example expands to something like
{\footnotesize\Large CONTENTS}
. In other words: The
\Large
in
\contentsname
always overwrites a previous font size selection. Therefore, instead of adding the font size to the
\…name
macros, the original problem should be addressed, namely changing the font size of the heading.

As already told, you can use one of the solutions of
Font size of Chapter number and Chapter Title
or
How to adjust the size and placement of chapter heading in report class
, which is linked as a duplicate of the first one. For example, you can use package
sectsty
:

\documentclass{book}

\usepackage{fancyhdr}
\pagestyle{fancy}
\fancypagestyle{frontmatterstyle}{%
\fancyhf{}%
\fancyhead[EC]{\footnotesize\leftmark}%
\fancyhead[OC]{\footnotesize Test}%
}

\usepackage{sectsty}
\chaptertitlefont{\Large}

\usepackage{lipsum}
\begin{document}
\frontmatter
\pagestyle{frontmatterstyle}
\tableofcontents
\listoffigures
\listoftables
\mainmatter
\chapter{Cha1}
\section{sec1}
\lipsum[1-8]
\end{document}

This reduces the font size of chapter headings without enlarging the font size of the page headers, because there are no longer font size commands in the
\…name
commands, which are used
after
your
\footnotesize
in the header definition.

You can use
\chaptertitlefont
several times, so it would also be possible to have inconsistent chapter headings (something I would never recommend):

\documentclass{book}

\usepackage{fancyhdr}
\pagestyle{fancy}
\fancypagestyle{frontmatterstyle}{%
\fancyhf{}%
\fancyhead[EC]{\footnotesize\leftmark}%
\fancyhead[OC]{\footnotesize Test}%
}

\usepackage{sectsty}

\usepackage{lipsum}
\begin{document}
\frontmatter
\pagestyle{frontmatterstyle}
\begingroup
\chaptertitlefont{\Large}
\tableofcontents
\endgroup
\begingroup
\chaptertitlefont{\normalsize\itshape}
\listoffigures
\listoftables
\endgroup
\mainmatter
\chapter{Cha1}
\section{sec1}
\lipsum[1-8]
\end{document}

Or you can bind the change to
\frontmatter
and
\mainmatter
:

\documentclass{book}

\usepackage{fancyhdr}
\pagestyle{fancy}
\fancypagestyle{frontmatterstyle}{%
\fancyhf{}%
\fancyhead[EC]{\footnotesize\leftmark}%
\fancyhead[OC]{\footnotesize Test}%
}

\usepackage{sectsty}
\AddToHook{cmd/frontmatter/after}{\chaptertitlefont{\Large}}% see lthooks-doc.pdf for more information
\AddToHook{cmd/mainmatter/after}{\chaptertitlefont{\Huge}}

\usepackage{lipsum}
\begin{document}
\ShowCommand{\frontmatter}
\frontmatter
\pagestyle{frontmatterstyle}
\tableofcontents
\listoffigures
\listoftables
\mainmatter
\chapter{Cha1}
\section{sec1}
\lipsum[1-8]
\end{document}

You could also use different fonts for numbered and for not numbered headings:

\documentclass{book}

\usepackage{fancyhdr}
\pagestyle{fancy}
\fancypagestyle{frontmatterstyle}{%
\fancyhf{}%
\fancyhead[EC]{\footnotesize\leftmark}%
\fancyhead[OC]{\footnotesize Test}%
}

\usepackage{xpatch}
\makeatletter
\xpatchcmd{\@makeschapterhead}{\Huge}{\Large}
{\typeout{\string\@makeschapterhead\space patched}}
{\errormessage{\string\@makeschapterhead\space patch failed}}
\makeatother

\usepackage{lipsum}
\begin{document}
\ShowCommand{\frontmatter}
\frontmatter
\pagestyle{frontmatterstyle}
\tableofcontents
\listoffigures
\listoftables
\mainmatter
\chapter{Cha1}
\section{sec1}
\lipsum[1-8]
\end{document}

Here I've more or less used
@Werner's answer to the second question linked above
, but instead of redefining
\@makeschapterhead
I've patched it, to replace the
\Huge
of the original definition by
\Large
.

Note: In the examples above, I've used your example with
fancyhdr
. But this package is only needed, if you want to change the page header and footer relative to the
report
default. It is not needed to avoid font size changes in the page header, when changing the font size of the headings of the table of contents or list of figures or list of tables or generally of not numbered chapters.

BTW: There are classes, which provide changing the font of headings without using additional packages or patching. For example,
scrreprt
would allow to use
\KOMAoptions{headings}{small}
or
\setkomafont{chapter}{\Large}
(and
can do this also several times inside the document
). With
memoir
you could use
\newcommand{\chaptitlefont}{\normalfont\Large\bfseries}
(also possible in the preamble and the document body). But these are only two examples. There are many more classes with configurable headings.

