Q: In ConTeXt/MetaFun, I am intentionally saving/redefining primitive tokens locally. For example:

\starttext

\startMPcode
def my_example =
begingroup;
save [; save ];
endgroup;
enddef;

my_example;
\stopMPcode

\stoptext

This produces a log message like:

metafun > log > overloading primitive '['
metafun > log > overloading primitive ']'

Is there a supported way to disable or suppress these specific MetaFun diagnostic messages?

I am not trying to hide TeX errors or MetaPost errors generally. I only want to suppress MetaFun’s informational logging about primitive overloading inside specific macros, because the logging is becoming unmanageable, i.e., hundreds of lines during just testing alone.

A: Answering your question exactly as asked

From MetaPost, you can set the
overloadmode
variable to
0
:

\startMPpage
overloadmode := 0;

def my_example =
begingroup;
save [; save ];
endgroup;
enddef;

my_example;
\stopMPpage

From TeX, you can set the
metapost.overloadmode
directive to
off
(or any string that isn't
warning
or
error
):

\enabledirectives[metapost.overloadmode=off]
\startMPpage
def my_example =
begingroup;
save [; save ];
endgroup;
enddef;

my_example;
\stopMPpage

Answering your problem in general

That that message either means that you're overloading a primitive, which you shouldn't do, so instead of trying to work around the message, I'd recommend using names other than
[
and
]
for your macros.

I don't know much MetaFun though, so there's a chance that this is a bug, in which case I'd recommend reporting it upstream rather than trying to work around it in your documents.

