Q: Is there a way to draw this parabola in plain tikz without getting a dimension error? I don't want to drag out the big guns for what seems like it should be a simple diagram.

\documentclass[tikz,border=1cm]{standalone}
\usetikzlibrary{calc}
\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}
\pgfmathsetmacro\FOCUSX{2}
\pgfmathsetmacro\FOCUSY{1}
\pgfmathsetmacro\LINEPX{-1}
\pgfmathsetmacro\LINEPY{0}
\pgfmathsetmacro\LINEDX{-3}
\pgfmathsetmacro\LINEDY{2}
\pgfmathsetmacro\LINEDL{sqrt((\LINEDX)^2 + (\LINEDY)^2)}
\pgfmathsetmacro\LINEDX{\LINEDX/\LINEDL}
\pgfmathsetmacro\LINEDY{\LINEDY/\LINEDL}
\pgfmathsetmacro\LINEPERPX{\LINEDY}
\pgfmathsetmacro\LINEPERPY{-\LINEDX}

% Focus
\fill (\FOCUSX,\FOCUSY)
node[right]{$F$} circle[radius=0.1];

% Directrix
\draw[dashed] (\LINEPX,\LINEPY)
-- +(7*\LINEDX,7*\LINEDY)
-- +(-7*\LINEDX,-7*\LINEDY);
\fill (\LINEPX,\LINEPY)
node[below left]{$P$} circle[radius=0.1];
\draw[->] (\LINEPX,\LINEPY) --
++(\LINEDX,\LINEDY) node[below left]{$D$};

% Directrix normal
\draw[->] (\LINEPX,\LINEPY) --
++(\LINEPERPX,\LINEPERPY) node[above left]{$N$};

\foreach \ALPHA in {-4,-3.5,...,4} {
\pgfmathsetmacro\QUADA{1-(\LINEPERPX)^2-(\LINEPERPY)^2}
\pgfmathsetmacro\QUADB{
\LINEPERPX*(\LINEPX+\ALPHA*\LINEDX-\FOCUSX)
+\LINEPERPY*(\LINEPY+\ALPHA*\LINEDY-\FOCUSY)
}
\pgfmathsetmacro\QUADB{-2*\QUADB}
\pgfmathsetmacro\QUADC{
(\LINEPX+\ALPHA*\LINEDX-\FOCUSX)^2
+(\LINEPY+\ALPHA*\LINEDY-\FOCUSY)^2
}
\pgfmathsetmacro\QUADC{-\QUADC}
\pgfmathsetmacro\BETA{
(-\QUADB+sqrt((\QUADB)^2-4*\QUADA*\QUADC))
/(2*\QUADA)
}
\fill[green] ($(\LINEPX,\LINEPY) + \ALPHA*(\LINEDX,\LINEDY) + \BETA*(\LINEPERPX,\LINEPERPY)$) circle[radius=0.1];
}

\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}

A: The point is that, once the normal vector has been normalized, we have

(\LinePerpX)^2+(\LinePerpY)^2=1
. Hence

\QuadA=1-(\LinePerpX)^2-(\LinePerpY)^2

is zero. Because of rounding, PGF may not get exactly zero, but rather
a very small nonzero number. Your formula then divides by this number,
which produces a huge coordinate. This is where the
Dimension too large

error comes from.

I would describe the parabola using coordinates associated with the directrix.
In these coordinates, the normal coordinate is given explicitly as a function
of the coordinate along the directrix. Here is a code example using this approach.

\documentclass[tikz,border=1cm]{standalone}

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}
\pgfmathsetmacro\FocusX{2}
\pgfmathsetmacro\FocusY{1}
\pgfmathsetmacro\LinePX{-1}
\pgfmathsetmacro\LinePY{0}
\pgfmathsetmacro\LineDX{-3}
\pgfmathsetmacro\LineDY{2}
\pgfmathsetmacro\LineDL{sqrt((\LineDX)^2 + (\LineDY)^2)}
\pgfmathsetmacro\LineDX{\LineDX/\LineDL}
\pgfmathsetmacro\LineDY{\LineDY/\LineDL}
\pgfmathsetmacro\LinePerpX{\LineDY}
\pgfmathsetmacro\LinePerpY{-\LineDX}

\pgfmathsetmacro\S{
(\FocusX-\LinePX)*\LineDX
+(\FocusY-\LinePY)*\LineDY
}
\pgfmathsetmacro\H{
(\FocusX-\LinePX)*\LinePerpX
+(\FocusY-\LinePY)*\LinePerpY
}

% Focus
\fill (\FocusX,\FocusY) node[right]{$F$} circle[radius=0.1];

% Directrix
\draw[dashed]
(\LinePX,\LinePY)
-- +(7*\LineDX,7*\LineDY)
-- +(-7*\LineDX,-7*\LineDY);

\fill (\LinePX,\LinePY) node[below left]{$P$} circle[radius=0.1];

\draw[->]
(\LinePX,\LinePY)
-- ++(\LineDX,\LineDY) node[below left]{$D$};

% Directrix normal
\draw[->]
(\LinePX,\LinePY)
-- ++(\LinePerpX,\LinePerpY) node[above left]{$N$};

% Parabola
\draw[green!60!black, thick, smooth, samples=100, domain=-4:4, variable=\Alpha]
plot
({
\LinePX+\Alpha*\LineDX
+(((\Alpha-\S)^2+\H^2)/(2*\H))*\LinePerpX
},
{
\LinePY+\Alpha*\LineDY
+(((\Alpha-\S)^2+\H^2)/(2*\H))*\LinePerpY
});

\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}

P.S.

I changed some of your all-caps names so that the code looks more presentable.

Edit 1.

Here is a detailed reply to Jasper's comment:

In a Cartesian coordinate system, we are given the focus
F=(2,1)
of the parabola, a point
P=(-1,0)
on its directrix, and a direction vector
D=(-3,2)
of the directrix.

Normalize the vector
D
.

After normalization, we keep the notation
D
for the resulting unit vector.

Construct a unit normal vector
N
to the directrix.

The subsequent computations are carried out in the coordinate system with origin at
P
and basis vectors
D
and
N
.

The focus has coordinates
(S,H)
, where

S=(F-P) dot D
,

H=(F-P) dot N
.

The normal vector
N
is chosen so that
H>0
. If
H<0
, we reverse the direction of
N
.

In the canonical coordinate system, the parabola has the equation

v^2=2pu
,

where
p
is the focal parameter, that is, the distance from the focus to the directrix.

Since
N
was chosen so that
H>0
, we have
p=H
, and the change-of-coordinates formulas from the
P,D,N
system to the canonical system are

u=beta-H/2
,

v=alpha-S
.

Substituting these into the canonical equation, we get

(alpha-S)^2=2H(beta-H/2)
,

and hence

beta=((alpha-S)^2+H^2)/(2H)
.

Edit 2.

Here is what seems to me to be a shorter and, more importantly, clearer version of the same code, taking into account the mathematics above.

\documentclass[tikz,border=1cm]{standalone}

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}
\pgfmathsetmacro\FocusX{2}
\pgfmathsetmacro\FocusY{1}
\pgfmathsetmacro\PointX{-1}
\pgfmathsetmacro\PointY{0}
\pgfmathsetmacro\DirX{-3}
\pgfmathsetmacro\DirY{2}

\pgfmathsetmacro\DirLen{sqrt((\DirX)^2+(\DirY)^2)}
\pgfmathsetmacro\DirX{\DirX/\DirLen}
\pgfmathsetmacro\DirY{\DirY/\DirLen}

\pgfmathsetmacro\NormX{\DirY}
\pgfmathsetmacro\NormY{-\DirX}

\pgfmathsetmacro\S{
(\FocusX-\PointX)*\DirX
+(\FocusY-\PointY)*\DirY
}
\pgfmathsetmacro\H{
(\FocusX-\PointX)*\NormX
+(\FocusY-\PointY)*\NormY
}

\ifdim\H pt<0pt
\pgfmathsetmacro\NormX{-\NormX}
\pgfmathsetmacro\NormY{-\NormY}
\pgfmathsetmacro\H{-\H}
\fi

\fill (\FocusX,\FocusY) node[right] {$F$} circle[radius=0.05];

\draw[dashed]
(\PointX,\PointY)
-- +(5*\DirX,5*\DirY)
-- +(-7*\DirX,-7*\DirY);

\fill (\PointX,\PointY) node[below left] {$P$} circle[radius=0.05];

\draw[thick,->] (\PointX,\PointY) -- ++(\DirX,\DirY) node[below left] {$D$};
\draw[thick,->] (\PointX,\PointY) -- ++(\NormX,\NormY) node[above left] {$N$};

\draw[green!60!black, thick, smooth, samples=50, domain=-4:5, variable=\Tv]
plot
({
\PointX + (\S+\Tv)*\DirX
+ (\H/2 + (\Tv)^2/(2*\H))*\NormX
},
{
\PointY + (\S+\Tv)*\DirY
+ (\H/2 + (\Tv)^2/(2*\H))*\NormY
});
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}

