A: The following example solves all of the OP's formatting objectives
except
for the one that postulates a
\shortref
macro, which is supposed to drop the theorem/lemma/proposition/corollary's "prefix" number. If you need to cross-reference individual enumerated properties in a
proof
that immediately follows a theorem/lemma/proposition/corollary, I trust it's not too burdensome to hardcode "(a)", "(b)", etc.

Note that by using
pdflatex-dev
or
lualatex-dev
instead of
pdflatex
or
lualatex
to compile the test document, it's no longer necessary to provide a host of "hooky" correction macros. (I seem to recall that starting with the June 2026 edition of the LaTeX format, one will be able to use "straight"
pdflatex
and
lualatex
as well.)

% !TEX TS-program = pdflatex-dev
\documentclass{amsart} % load 'amsthm' automatically
\usepackage{iftex} \ifpdftex \usepackage[T1]{fontenc} \fi
\usepackage{enumitem}
\usepackage{cleveref}

\newtheorem{theorem}{Theorem}[section]
\newtheorem{corollary}[theorem]{Corollary}
\newtheorem{lemma}[theorem]{Lemma}
\newtheorem{proposition}[theorem]{Proposition}

\newlist{thmlist}{enumerate}{1}
\setlist[thmlist]{%
label= \textnormal{\bfseries\upshape(\alph*)},
ref = \thetheorem.\alph*,
left = 0pt, nosep}
\crefname{thmlisti}{Property}{Properties}

\begin{document}

\section{Math}

\begin{theorem} \label{thm:x}
If $X$ is \dots, then $X$ has the following properties:
\begin{thmlist}
\item \label{it:a} Property a \dots
\item \label{it:b} Property b \dots
\end{thmlist}
\end{theorem}

\begin{lemma}\label{lemma:z}$Z$ satisfies \dots \end{lemma}

\begin{corollary}\label{cor:u}$U$ satisfies \dots \end{corollary}

\begin{proposition}\label{prop:v}$V$ satisfies:
\begin{thmlist}
\item \label{it:ab} Property $\alpha\beta$ \dots
\item \label{it:cd} Property $\gamma\delta$ \dots
\end{thmlist}
\end{proposition}

\bigskip\noindent
Cross-references to \cref{thm:x,lemma:z,cor:u,prop:v}.

\medskip\noindent
We see that $\kappa$ and $\lambda$ satisfy \cref{it:a,it:cd}.

\end{document}

Addendum
: Speaking for myself (who else?), I think your readers might appreciate if you don't overburden cross-references to items in a theorem-like list. Thus, instead of outputting "Property 1.1.a", consider outputing "Property (a) of Theorem 1.1". Of course, you're free to call items in the theorem-like list some other than "properties".

% !TEX TS-program = pdflatex-dev
\documentclass{amsart} % load 'amsthm' automatically
\usepackage{iftex} \ifpdftex \usepackage[T1]{fontenc} \fi
\usepackage{enumitem}
\usepackage{cleveref}

\newtheorem{theorem}{Theorem}[section]
\newtheorem{corollary}[theorem]{Corollary}
\newtheorem{lemma}[theorem]{Lemma}
\newtheorem{proposition}[theorem]{Proposition}

\newlist{thmlist}{enumerate}{1}
\setlist[thmlist]{%
label= \textnormal{\bfseries\upshape(\alph*)},
ref = \upshape(\alph*),
left = 0pt, nosep}
\crefname{thmlisti}{property}{properties}

\begin{document}

\section{Math}

\begin{theorem} \label{thm:x}
If $X$ is \dots, then $X$ has the following properties:
\begin{thmlist}
\item \label{it:a} Property a \dots
\item \label{it:b} Property b \dots
\end{thmlist}
\end{theorem}

\begin{lemma}\label{lemma:z}$Z$ satisfies \dots \end{lemma}

\begin{corollary}\label{cor:u}$U$ satisfies \dots \end{corollary}

\begin{proposition}\label{prop:v}$V$ satisfies:
\begin{thmlist}
\item \label{it:ab} Property $\alpha\beta$ \dots
\item \label{it:cd} Property $\gamma\delta$ \dots
\end{thmlist}
\end{proposition}

\bigskip\noindent
$\kappa$ and $\lambda$ satisfy \cref{it:a} of \cref{thm:x} and \cref{it:cd} of \cref{prop:v}.

\end{document}

