Note: Both must be similar. Right now both are not similar.

A: I propose a purely analytic solution. Namely, draw the blue arc parametrically, shifting each point of the ellipse by
1cm
in the direction of the inward normal to the ellipse.

Note that, because of ultra thick, the visual gap between the edges of the lines will be slightly less than
1cm
.

The numbers
84.94
,
8.83
, and
-1.03
can be adjusted by trial and error from the picture, or they can be obtained by solving the corresponding equations numerically.

\documentclass[tikz,margin=1cm]{standalone}
\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}
\draw[gray!50] (-8,0) grid (8,-8);
\fill (0,0) node[above=12pt]{origin} circle (5pt);

\draw[ultra thick]
(-6,0)
arc[x radius=12,y radius=8,start angle=90,end angle=0]
-- (-6,-8)
-- cycle;

\draw[blue,ultra thick]
(-5,-1.03)
plot[
variable=\t,
domain=84.94:8.83,
samples=100
]
(
{-6 + 12*cos(\t)
- (cos(\t)/12)/sqrt((cos(\t)/12)^2 + (sin(\t)/8)^2)},
{-8 + 8*sin(\t)
- (sin(\t)/8)/sqrt((cos(\t)/12)^2 + (sin(\t)/8)^2)}
)
-- (-5,-7)
-- cycle;

\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}

