A: I think the main improvement is to compute the x-intercept rather than specify it manually.
If the regression line is given by

y = 34 + x*tan(20)
,
then its slope is

m = tan(20)
.
Therefore, a line perpendicular to the regression line has slope

-1/m
.

For the point
P = (200, 34 + 200*tan(20))
, the equation of the perpendicular line passing through
P
is

y - (34 + 200*tan(20)) = -(x - 200)/tan(20)
.
Setting
y = 0
, we obtain the
x
-coordinate of the intersection with the
x
-axis:

x = 200 + (34 + 200*tan(20))*tan(20)
.

This is exactly the value denoted by
\xtt
in my code.

There is some confusion with the point
P
in the code given in the question.

In one place, it is defined as

\coordinate (P) at (axis cs:200, {36 + 200*tan(20)});

In another place, the intended point seems to be the point with coordinates
(200,105.6)
.

If, however, the point P is supposed to lie on the regression line

y = 34 + x*tan(20)
,
then it should be defined as

\coordinate (P) at (axis cs:200, {34 + 200*tan(20)});

I constructed the perpendicular under the assumption that the point
P
lies on the regression line, that is, according to case 3.

I replaced the lines

% Perpendicular line from the 3rd circle (x=300)
\coordinate (P) at (axis cs:200, {36 + 200*tan(20)});
\draw [very thick, black] (P) -- (axis cs:252.1, 0);

with the lines

% Perpendicular line from the point at x=200
\coordinate (P) at (axis cs:200, {34 + 200*tan(20)});
\pgfmathsetmacro{\xtt}{200 + (34 + 200*tan(20))*tan(20)}
\draw [very thick, black] (P) -- (axis cs:\xtt, 0);

