A: You can use
expl3
, although the business can be done also without it. You don't need
\fp_to_decimal:n
because
\fp_eval:n
suffices.

% Source - https://tex.stackexchange.com/q/762765
% Posted by tkl
% Retrieved 2026-05-13, License - CC BY-SA 4.0

\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{datavisualization}

\begin{document}

\ExplSyntaxOn
\NewDocumentCommand{\tologarithmic}{mm}
{
\tkl_tologarithmic:ee {\fp_eval:n {ln(#1)/ln(10)}} {\fp_eval:n {ln(#2)/ln(10)}}
}
\cs_new_protected:Nn \tkl_tologarithmic:nn
{
\pgfkeyssetvalue{/data~point/x}{#1}
\pgfkeyssetvalue{/data~point/y}{#2}
\pgfdatapoint
}
\cs_generate_variant:Nn \tkl_tologarithmic:nn {ee}
\ExplSyntaxOff

\pgfdeclaredataformat{compute}{}{}{#1 #2}% line format
{\tologarithmic{#1}{#2}}% code
{}{}

\begin{tikzpicture}
\datavisualization[scientific axes,
visualize as scatter,
]
data[format=compute,set=scatter] {
2.868E+03 2.804E-02
5.636E+04 2.061E-02
1.791E+06 1.079E-02
3.554E+07 7.080E-03
};
\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}

Remember to never use
\def
(unless it's really necessary, which it isn't here).

The idea is to pass the expanded arguments to the function that sets the value for
datavisualization
.

cfr's answer
shows how to do it without
expl3
.

