A: The following works with either
beamer
or its successor
ltx-talk
(but tagging would obviously require more work).

I simplified the example a bit to experiment more easily, so there is only 1 frame and I used the default geometry etc. However, the code uses
\linewidth
and
\textheight
, so it should work with any page dimensions.

As I understand the
tikz
manual,
current page
requires
remember picture
and
overlay
, but that cannot work here. So the basic idea is to use the text area instead. We create
C
relative to the bounding box and set this for
baseline
to the
tikzpicture
. We also tell
beamer
that the page content has the required width and height, regardless of what it may think about it.

% Source - https://tex.stackexchange.com/q/762748
% Posted by Jasper
% Retrieved 2026-05-13, License - CC BY-SA 4.0
\documentclass{beamer}

\usepackage{pgfplots,tikz-3dplot,animate,tikzducks}
\pgfplotsset{compat=1.18}

\newsavebox{\titlebox}
\sbox{\titlebox}{%
\parbox{\textwidth}{%
\centering
{\Large\bfseries Overfull \textbackslash{}dbox}\par\vskip 1.5em
{\normalsize Jasper Nice}\par\vskip 0.8em
{\small Today}%
}%
}
\begin{document}

\begin{frame}
\centering
\begin{overlayarea}{\linewidth}{\textheight}
\begin{animateinline}[autoplay]{10}%
\pgfplotsforeachungrouped \FRAME in {1,...,60} {%
\tdplotsetmaincoords{90-90*\FRAME/68}{-90+90*\FRAME/68}%
\begin{tikzpicture}[x=\linewidth,y=\textheight,baseline=(C)]
\useasboundingbox (0,0) rectangle (\linewidth,\textheight);
\coordinate (C) at (current bounding box.center);
\begin{scope}[tdplot_main_coords]
\node[canvas is xy plane at z=0,transform shape] at (C) {\usebox{\titlebox}};
\begin{scope}[canvas is yz plane at x=0,shift=(C)]
\duck
\end{scope}
\end{scope}
\end{tikzpicture}%
\pgfmathsetmacro{\III}{\FRAME != 60}%
\ifnum\III=1\newframe\else\newframe
\tdplotsetmaincoords{0}{0}%
\begin{tikzpicture}[x=\linewidth,y=\textheight]
\useasboundingbox (0,0) rectangle (\linewidth,\textheight);
\coordinate (C) at (current bounding box.center);
\begin{scope}[tdplot_main_coords]
\node[canvas is xy plane at z=0,transform shape] at (C) {\usebox{\titlebox}};
\end{scope}
\end{tikzpicture}%
\fi
}%
\end{animateinline}%
\end{overlayarea}
\end{frame}

\end{document}

It may be that some changes are not strictly necessary.

Note that this does complain of overfull boxes, but I am not sure how to eliminate those in this case.

