Q: I am writing a document whose main language is French.
A whole section is in English
\section{Abstract}

And then other sections are in French
\section{Résumé}

\section{Méthodes}
etc.
I would like the English section to respect English typographic rules (note only punctuation or quotes) and other sections in French to respect French typographic rules.
Writing
\selectlanguage{english}
or using
otherlanguage
environment only change the locale language which changes how quotes render for example, but it does not change first paragraph indentation nor the
\labelitemi

Is it possible to switch the main language for a whole section ?
Thereafter a minimal example:

\documentclass[paperletter, 12pt, english, french]{article}
\usepackage{babel}
\usepackage[inline]{enumitem}
\usepackage{lipsum}
\title{Plain Latex}

\begin{document}

\section{Français}
Une liste en français
\begin{itemize}
\item La langue \og principale\fg{} est : \mainlocalename !
\item La langue \og courante\fg{} est : \localename ;
\end{itemize}

\lipsum[1][1-3]\par
\lipsum[1][4-6]
\selectlanguage{english}
\section{English}
A list in English
\begin{itemize}
\item The \og main\fg{} language is : \mainlocalename !
\item The \og current\fg{} language is : \localename ;
\end{itemize}

\lipsum[2][1-3]\par
\lipsum[2][4-6]\par
\subsection{poor patches}
\noindent
\lipsum[3][1-3]\par
\lipsum[3][4-6]\par
\begin{itemize}[label={\textbullet}]
\item The \og main\fg{} language is : \mainlocalename !
\item The \og current\fg{} language is : \localename ;
\end{itemize}
\end{document}

A: Good typography is consistent. Of course, a change of language requires adaption to that language's typographical conventions, but, where those conventions do not necessitate it, I would strongly recommend keeping the same settings.

This means that hyphenation patterns, quotation marks, label names and punctuation should change when you switch between French and English. But to the best of my knowledge, there is no convention in English typography dictating the symbols used for different levels of unordered lists or indentation following a heading. Leslie Lamport decided against indentation following a heading. That is probably more common in American typography than British, but it is certainly not universal. Likewise with bullets etc., where I honestly doubt there is even any consistent trend.

I do not know if French typographic conventions require indentation following a heading or particular symbols for particular levels of unordered listings. If they do not, pick whichever you prefer and stick to it. If they do, use the same settings for the English passages.

What does matter are at least the following:

hyphenation patterns (handled by
babel
);

quotation marks (somewhat handled by
babel
);

spacing around punctuation;

punctuation following quotation marks.

Some of these items differ between different variants of English. It is therefore important that you select the
correct
variant of English.

If you do not, you will not get correct hyphenation.

Moreover, punctuation following quotation marks moves in US English, whereas it is does not in UK English. American English is more similar to French here, but French, as I understand it, will also move a footnote marker, whereas US English does not go that far.

For French, you must load
fontenc
with the
T1
(or similar) encoding unless you are using a Unicode engine. The default text font encoding does not support French typography.

You also need to adjust spacing around e.g. colons for English of any stripe.

\item The \og main\fg{} language is : \mainlocalename !
\item The \og current\fg{} language is : \localename ;

This is wrong. The following is better, but still wrong:

\item The \og main\fg{} language is: \mainlocalename !
\item The \og current\fg{} language is: \localename ;

Language names are proper names, so must be capitalised.

\item The \og main\fg{} language is: \MakeTitlecase{\mainlocalename} !
\item The \og current\fg{} language is: \MakeTitlecase{\localename} ;

This sorts the capitalisation, but changes the spacing. To correct that, we can use

\item The \og main\fg{} language is: \MakeTitlecase{\mainlocalename}!
\item The \og current\fg{} language is: \MakeTitlecase{\localename};

Note that the quotation marks you are using are correct for US English outer quotation marks, but wrong for UK English, where single quotation marks are used for the outer level.

You can get better results for quotations using
csquotes
. In theory, this is able to move trailing punctuation inside quotations, but I cannot currently get this to work. (Probably my fault, but I gave up.)

The other thing which French
babel
does is alter the style of float labels, but only for French. Again, I don't know if this is required by French typography, but there is certainly no such requirement for English, so I would enforce consistency here, too. The
caption
package can help with this. For example, the following modifies the labels outside French to use small-caps. Other adjustments may also be wanted here. If so,
caption
is quite flexible in terms of the modifications it can help with.

Note that unless you changed the TeX Live default, use a distribution with a different default or otherwise did something, you will get A4 paper by default with US letter layout
1
.
geometry
will correct this.

As Mico pointed out

paperletter
does nothing but produce a warning telling you it does nothing.
letterpaper
is presumably intended here.

% Source - https://tex.stackexchange.com/q/762715
% Posted by ncdipde
% Retrieved 2026-05-12, License - CC BY-SA 4.0

\documentclass[letterpaper,12pt,american,french]{article}
\usepackage{babel}
\usepackage[T1]{fontenc}% or use lualatex
\usepackage{geometry}% needed unless you changed the default when installing
\usepackage[autostyle=true,autopunct=true]{csquotes}% possibly
\usepackage[inline]{enumitem}
\usepackage[labelfont=sc]{caption}
\usepackage{lipsum}
\title{Plain Latex}

\begin{document}

\section{Français}
Une liste en français \figurename
\begin{itemize}
\item La langue \og principale\fg{} est : \mainlocalename !
\item La langue \enquote{courante} est : \localename ;
\end{itemize}
\begin{figure}
\caption{A}\label{fig:A}
\end{figure}
\textquote{La langue principale n'est pas le chinois.\footnote{a}}
\begin{table}
\caption{A}\label{tab:A}
\end{table}

\lipsum[1][1-3]\par
\lipsum[1][4-6]
\selectlanguage{english}
\section{English}
A list in English \figurename
\begin{itemize}
\item The \og main\fg{} language is: \MakeTitlecase{\mainlocalename}!
\item The \enquote{current} language is: \MakeTitlecase{\localename};
\end{itemize}
\begin{figure}
\caption{B}\label{fig:B}
\end{figure}
\textquote{The main language is not Chinese.}\footnote{a}
\begin{table}
\caption{B}\label{tab:B}
\end{table}

\lipsum[2][1-3]\par
\lipsum[2][4-6]\par
\end{document}

