A: As pointed out in the comments, you are explicitly adding spaces, including one at the start of the node. There is no paragraph indentation in nodes by default, so setting it to zero doesn't make any difference and won't remove regular interword spacing.

I would take the font and spacing macros out of the node and use
font
to set the text style. Then we have something like this:

% Source - https://tex.stackexchange.com/q/762679
% Posted by aky-her, modified by community. See post 'Timeline' for change history
% Retrieved 2026-05-10, License - CC BY-SA 4.0

\documentclass{article}

\usepackage[paperheight=8cm, paperwidth=6cm, left=0pt, top=0pt, right=0pt, bottom=0pt]{geometry}

\usepackage{tikz}

\usepackage{fontspec}
\setmainfont{TeX Gyre Cursor}

\newcommand{\setfontsz}[1]{% <= don't add a space
\fontsize{#1}{1.2#1}% <= don't add a space
\selectfont
}

\pagestyle{empty}

\newcommand{\sztext}{8pt}

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[remember picture, overlay, shift = {(current page.south west)}]
\node at (current page.center) [] {\includegraphics[height=\paperheight]{example-image-a.png}};
\node at (3, 1.75) [align = left,text width = 4.6cm,font=\bfseries\setfontsz{\sztext}, ]
{Text line 1, Longer text line 2, Even way way way way longer text line 3, Text line 4}; % <= don't add a space before the first `T`
\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}

align=left
sets the text
\raggedright
more-or-less.

Q: I wanted the text "This page intentionally left blank." to appear in the
book
class whenever a new chapter starts leaving the preceding even page empty. I solved this problem a few years ago by adding the following code to the preamble:

\makeatletter
\def\cleardoublepage{\clearpage%
\if@twoside
\ifodd\c@page\else
\vspace*{\fill}
\hfill
\begin{center}
\emph{This page intentionally left blank.}
\end{center}
\vspace{\fill}
\thispagestyle{empty}
\newpage
\if@twocolumn\hbox{}\newpage\fi
\fi
\fi
}
\makeatother

Recently, I noticed that the page following
\part
was completely empty. I found the solution here
“This page intentionally left blank” after \part
, where it was suggested to modify the
\@endpart
command as follows:

\makeatletter
\def\@endpart{\vfil\newpage\if@twoside \if@openright
\mbox{}
\vspace*{\fill}
\begin{center}
\emph{This page intentionally left blank.}
\end{center}
\vspace{\fill}
\thispagestyle{empty}
\newpage\fi\fi
\if@tempswa\twocolumn\fi}
\makeatother

However, when formatting the titles with
titlesec
, the problem reappears: pages inserted after
\part
are completely empty, ignoring the previous instructions. Nevertheless, the empty page before
\part
correctly mainteins the text "This page intentionally left blank.". Is there a way to solve this problem? Below is a minimal working example showing what I have been able to achieve so far:

\documentclass{book}

% This page intentionally left blank
\makeatletter
\def\cleardoublepage{\clearpage%
\if@twoside
\ifodd\c@page\else
\vspace*{\fill}
\hfill
\begin{center}
\emph{This page intentionally left blank.}
\end{center}
\vspace{\fill}
\thispagestyle{empty}
\newpage
\if@twocolumn\hbox{}\newpage\fi
\fi
\fi
}
\makeatother

% This page intentionally left blank after "\part"
\makeatletter
\def\@endpart{\vfil\newpage\if@twoside \if@openright
\mbox{}
\vspace*{\fill}
\begin{center}
\emph{This page intentionally left blank.}
\end{center}
\vspace{\fill}
\thispagestyle{empty}
\newpage\fi\fi
\if@tempswa\twocolumn\fi}
\makeatother

\usepackage{titlesec}
\usepackage{xcolor}
\titleformat{\part}[display]{\centering\sffamily\huge\bfseries\color{red}}{\partname\ \thepart}{20pt}{\Huge}

\begin{document}

Text

\part{Text}

Text

\end{document}

A: With
titlesec
, i.e., after using
\titleformat{\part}…
command
\part
is redefined an does not use
\@endpart
any longer. Instead it used internal commands of
titlesec
, i.e.,
\ttl@page@ii
. So you would need to redefine or patch internal commands of
titlesec

after
loading the package. In the following example I'm replacing the
\null
used to start the empty page in
\ttl@page@ii
by the content for the intentionally left blank page. I'm using
package
xpatch
to do the patch.

\documentclass{book}

% This page intentionally left blank
\makeatletter
\def\cleardoublepage{\clearpage%
\if@twoside
\ifodd\c@page\else
\intentionallyleftblank
\thispagestyle{empty}
\newpage
\if@twocolumn\hbox{}\newpage\fi
\fi
\fi
}
\makeatother

\newcommand\intentionallyleftblank{%
\vspace*{\fill}
\hfill
\begin{center}
\emph{This page intentionally left blank.}
\end{center}
\vspace{\fill}
}

\usepackage{titlesec}
\usepackage{xpatch}
\makeatletter
\xpatchcmd{\ttl@page@ii}{\null}
{%
\intentionallyleftblank
}
{\typeout{\protect\ttl@page@ii\space patch successfull}}
{\typeout{\protect\ttl@page@ii\space patch failed}}
\makeatother

\usepackage{xcolor}
\titleformat{\part}[display]{\centering\sffamily\huge\bfseries\color{red}}{\partname\ \thepart}{20pt}{\Huge}

\begin{document}

Text

\part{Text}

Text

\end{document}

Caveat: It is always a hack to redefine or patch an internal command of (either LaTeX, a class or) a package. So the solution here may work or may not work if
titlesec
internals change. It is tested with the current
titlesec
release 2025/01/04 v2.17.

