A: You can avoid guessing.

\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

% a general purpose macro
\newcommand{\xmathpalette}[2]{\mathchoice
{#1\displaystyle\textfont{#2}}%
{#1\textstyle\textfont{#2}}%
{#1\scriptstyle\scriptfont{#2}}%
{#1\scriptscriptstyle\scriptscriptfont{#2}}%
}

\makeatletter
\newcommand{\myge}{\mathrel{\xmathpalette\mygele@{\long@bar\short@bar}}}
\newcommand{\myle}{\mathrel{\xmathpalette\mygele@{\short@bar\long@bar}}}
\newcommand{\mygele@}[3]{\mygele@@{#1}{#2}#3}
\newcommand{\mygele@@}[4]{%
\begingroup
\sbox\z@{$#1=$}%
\vbox{
\m@th
\hbox{\raisebox{\dimeval{\ht\z@-\fontdimen22 #2 2-0.5\fontdimen8 #2 3}}[0pt][0pt]{$#1#3$}}%
\nointerlineskip
\hbox{\raisebox{\dimeval{0.5\fontdimen8 #2 3 + \fontdimen22 #2 2-\ht\z@}}[0pt][0pt]{$#1#4$}}%
}
\endgroup
}
\newcommand{\long@bar}{{-}\mkern-8mu{-}\mkern-8mu{-}}
\newcommand{\short@bar}{-}
\makeatother

\begin{document}

$a\myge b$ $a\myle b$

$\myge = \myle$

$\scriptstyle a\myge b\myle c$

\end{document}

With NewTX there is a very slight misalignment with =, but I wouldn't bother because the symbols will never be side-by-side.

A variant with a shorter long bar

\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
%\usepackage{newtx}

% a general purpose macro
\newcommand{\xmathpalette}[2]{\mathchoice
{#1\displaystyle\textfont{#2}}%
{#1\textstyle\textfont{#2}}%
{#1\scriptstyle\scriptfont{#2}}%
{#1\scriptscriptstyle\scriptscriptfont{#2}}%
}

\makeatletter
\newcommand{\myge}{\mathrel{\xmathpalette\mygele@{\long@bar\short@bar}}}
\newcommand{\myle}{\mathrel{\xmathpalette\mygele@{\short@bar\long@bar}}}
\newcommand{\mygele@}[3]{\mygele@@{#1}{#2}#3}
\newcommand{\mygele@@}[4]{%
\begingroup
\let\mygele@style=#1%
\sbox\z@{$#1=$}%
\vbox{
\m@th
\hbox{\raisebox{\dimeval{\ht\z@-\fontdimen22 #2 2-0.5\fontdimen8 #2 3}}[0pt][0pt]{$#1#3$}}%
\nointerlineskip
\hbox{\raisebox{\dimeval{0.5\fontdimen8 #2 3 + \fontdimen22 #2 2-\ht\z@}}[0pt][0pt]{$#1#4$}}%
}
\endgroup
}
\newcommand{\long@bar}{%
\sbox\tw@{$\mygele@style-$}%
\makebox[1.5\wd\tw@][s]{\usebox\tw@\hss\usebox\tw@\hss\usebox\tw@}%
}
\newcommand{\short@bar}{-}
\makeatother

\begin{document}

$a\myge b$ $a\myle b$

$\myge = \myle$

$\scriptstyle a\myge b\myle c$

\end{document}

Adapt the 1.5 factor to your liking.

Q: I have been asked to introduced negated mathrel symbols in NewCM that do not exist in Unicode standard. Before I get into adding extra symbols in NewCMMath I would like to make sure that a macro does not suffice. I tested with the
\not
command or relative packages like centernot without good results. Then there is
\ooalign
. For example,

\documentclass{article}
\usepackage[olddefault]{fontsetup}
\makeatletter
\newcommand{\ndisin}{\mathrel{\mathpalette\overlay@slash\disin}}
\newcommand{\overlay@slash}[2]{%
\ooalign{$\m@th#1#2$\cr\hss$\m@th#1/$\hss}%
}
\makeatother
\begin{document}
$y\ndisin A_{y\ndisin A_{y\ndisin A}}$
\end{document}

Produces

This shows that exactly centering the two symbols is not always good. The slash should be better placed a bit to the right (centered with respect to
\in
). So the question is if it is possible to make such adjustments on the above or other code to get the desired result, or one has to go to the font level and design new characters.

A: I'd go with
\notaccent
, so when doing copy-paste you get something meaningful.

You can add some kerning to move the bar a bit to the right.

\documentclass{article}
\usepackage[olddefault]{fontsetup}
%\usepackage{lum-stix2}

\DeclareRobustCommand{\ndisin}{%
\mathrel{%
\mkern3mu\notaccent{\mkern-3mu\disin}%
}%
}

\begin{document}

$y\ndisin A_{y\ndisin A_{y\ndisin A}}$

\end{document}

If I reverse the comments to use STIX2, I get

Addendum

Unfortunately, XeTeX doesn't know about overlay accents. If you plan to also support XeLaTeX,

\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{iftex}
\usepackage[olddefault]{fontsetup}

\ifxetex
\usepackage{centernot}
\makeatletter
\DeclareRobustCommand{\ndisin}{\mathrel{\mathpalette\ndisin@\relax}}
\newcommand{\ndisin@}[2]{%
\ooalign{%
\hidewidth
$\m@th#1\mkern12mu\Umathchar"0 \symoperators "0338$%
\hidewidth\cr
$\m@th#1\disin$\cr
}%
}
\makeatother
\else
\DeclareRobustCommand{\ndisin}{%
\mathrel{%
\mkern3mu\notaccent{\mkern-3mu\disin}%
}%
}
\fi

\begin{document}

\texttt{\ifxetex xe\else lua\fi latex}

$y\ndisin A_{y\ndisin A_{y\ndisin A}}$

\end{document}

