A: It seems that the cause is indeed
\xspace
. It inserts a space if the following token is not included in its list of exceptions. The standard list contains
)
, but not
]
, so no space is inserted before
)
, whereas it is inserted before
]
. Add the following line after
\usepackage{xspace}
:

\xspaceaddexceptions{]}

It is also worth mentioning that everything works fine for me if I define

\newcommand{\tss}[1]{\textsuperscript{#1}}

without
\xspace
.

Q: First an MWE is as follows.

\documentclass{article}

\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{amsthm}

\begin{document}

\begin{proof}
\begin{align*}{2}
x&=y&\quad&\text{test test}\\
&=z&&\text{test.}\qedhere
\end{align*}
\end{proof}

\end{document}

As you see, to make the texts be aligned left, I add an empty column in the
align*
environment. But the width of the empty column is too big, so is there any way to specify it? By the way, I have to use
align*
or
align
to make the square be aligned to right in the final line in proofs.

Summary

Combining @cfr 's solution and
the solution here
, the problem is solved.

A: Answer for Updated Question

align*
doesn't provide this feature. Instead, you can use
alignat*
. If the lines are part of a larger block, you can use
alignedat
.

\documentclass{article}

\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{amsthm}

\begin{document}
\begin{proof}
\begin{align*}
&\begin{alignedat}[b]{2}
x&=y&\quad&\text{test test} \\
&=z&&\text{test.}
\end{alignedat}&&\qedhere
\end{align*}
\end{proof}

\end{document}

Answer for Original Question

alignat
is designed for this, as
align
is not. From
amsmath
's manual (page 8):

A variant environment
alignat
allows the horizontal space between
equations to be explicitly specified.

That is,
alignat
is designed to be just like
align
except you control the spacing between the columns. As with
alignat
, so with
alignat*
.

\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

\begin{alignat*}{2}
x&=y&\quad&\text{test test}\\
&=z&&\text{test.}
\end{alignat*}

\end{document}

